{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658650"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:52:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:52:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20808"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20808"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.83,0,0.17,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13683"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96900"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13683"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20808"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79515"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11578"},{"type":"tags","id":"11742"},{"type":"tags","id":"12641"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32954"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32955"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96900"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe plasma membrane forms the boundary between the cell and its external environment, serving multiple functions essential for cellular survival.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how the plasma membrane provides protection to cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["By forming a phospholipid bilayer with selective permeability","By expressing glycoproteins that mediate cell recognition","By stabilizing membrane fluidity with cholesterol","By maintaining electrochemical gradients across the membrane","By anchoring the cytoskeleton to membrane proteins"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe plasma membrane provides protection to cells primarily by \u003Cstrong\u003Estabilizing membrane fluidity with cholesterol\u003C/strong\u003E. Cholesterol molecules insert between phospholipids in the membrane, preventing phospholipid fatty acid chains from packing too tightly at lower temperatures (preventing excessive rigidity) while also limiting their movement at higher temperatures (preventing excessive fluidity). This balanced fluidity is essential for maintaining membrane integrity and protective function across varying environmental conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBy forming a phospholipid bilayer with selective permeability\u003C/strong\u003E - While the phospholipid bilayer does provide a barrier with selective permeability, this is a general structural feature rather than the specific protective mechanism that cholesterol provides through fluidity regulation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBy expressing glycoproteins that mediate cell recognition\u003C/strong\u003E - Glycoproteins are important for cell recognition and signaling, but they are not primarily responsible for the protective physical barrier function of the membrane.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBy maintaining electrochemical gradients across the membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - Electrochemical gradients are essential for cellular function but are a consequence of membrane integrity rather than a primary protective mechanism.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBy anchoring the cytoskeleton to membrane proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - While this connection provides structural support, it does not directly regulate the protective barrier properties of the membrane as effectively as cholesterol does.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to cholesterol\u0027s role in membrane stability, the plasma membrane provides protection through other mechanisms including: specialised junctional complexes that maintain tissue integrity, receptor proteins that detect environmental threats, and the phospholipid bilayer itself which creates a hydrophobic barrier against water-soluble molecules and ions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The plasma membrane provides protection to cells through its selective permeability and structural integrity.","Cholesterol is a key component that stabilizes the plasma membrane and regulates its fluidity.","Membrane proteins like integrins and cadherins provide structural support and cell-cell adhesion that protect cellular integrity."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 1, The Cell as a Unit of Health and Disease; p. 8-11"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79515"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20808"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79515"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T12:34:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T12:36:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13683"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96900"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co